Because in Java, the array is 0-based. So in Fortran, since we sorted AB in 1-based index, when i is 1 in Java, it's i=1 in Fortran, so AB(i-1) becomes AB(0) in Java but in Fortran, i starts at 1, so AB(i) is the ith element. Wait, no. Let's re-examine. Java code:

for (int i = 1; i <= N; i++) {

   int time = AB[i-1][0];

   int value = AB[i-1][1];

} So when i is 1, AB[0] is accessed. So in Fortran, if the AB array is 1-based, then for i in 1..N, the current AB element is AB(i, 1) and AB(i, 2). So in the Fortran code, when i is from 1 to N (since the loop is i=1 to N in Java), then in Fortran, the same loop would be i from 1 to N. So time = AB(i, 1), value = AB(i, 2). So the code for Fortran would have:

time = AB(i, 1)

value = AB(i, 2)

Then, check if 0 <= timeAfterEat - time and timeAfterEat - time < T. So timeAfterEat - time >=0 and < T.

If so, then:

dp(i, timeAfterEat) = max(dp(i, timeAfterEat), dp(i-1, timeAfterEat - time) + value)
